  "prompt": "Does my duck have hypothermia?",
  "response": "Determining if your duck has hypothermia involves observing its behavior and physical condition. Here are some signs to look for:\n\n1. **Shivering**: Like other animals, ducks may shiver when they are cold.\n2. **Lethargy**: A duck with hypothermia may appear unusually tired or inactive.\n3. **Huddling**: Ducks may huddle together or seek shelter when they are cold.\n4. **Cold to the touch**: If you check its body temperature and it's significantly lower than normal (duck body temperature is typically around 104 to 107\u00b0F or 40 to 42\u00b0C), it may have hypothermia.\n5. **Fluffed feathers**: Ducks puff up their feathers to trap warmth, so if it\u2019s fluffed and not moving much, it could indicate cold stress.\n6. **Weakness**: Difficulty standing or walking may be a sign of hypothermia or other health issues.\n\nIf you suspect your duck may have hypothermia, it's important to warm it up gradually. Move it to a warm, dry place away from drafts, and provide some warmth with blankets or a heat lamp. \n\nIf the duck shows severe symptoms or does not improve quickly, consult a veterinarian experienced with birds for further guidance.",
